{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569661"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:31:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:31:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22283"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22283","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22283"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.63,0.25,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15248"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114820"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15248","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15248"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22283"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96824"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"},{"type":"tags","id":"12955"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40349"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40350"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40935"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43768"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48427"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114820"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for her annual health check. She has a medical history of stage 3a chronic kidney disease (CKD), hypertension, and pre-diabetes diagnosed one year ago. Her regular medications include perindopril, and atorvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Most recent blood tests show an estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR) of 49 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 and a urine albumin-creatinine ratio (uACR) of 2.6 mg/mmol (\u0026lt;3 mg/mmol).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate review frequency for blood tests this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Every 1-3 months","Every 3-6 months","Every 12 months","Every 2 years","Every 3 years"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has stage 3a CKD (eGFR 49 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2) with normoalbuminuria (uACR 2.6 mg/mmol), on a background of hypertension and pre-diabetes. These factors influence the appropriate monitoring frequency in primary care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEvery 12 months\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate review frequency for this patient, and corresponds to the \u0027yellow action plan\u0027 in the traffic-light system used for CKD management in primary care. Patient cohorts that fit in the yellow action plan group include those with an eGFR \u226560 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 with microalbuminuria (A2) or those with eGFR 45-59 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 with normoalbuminuria (A1) - the latter of which applies to the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEvery 1-3 months\u003C/strong\u003E review frequency corresponds to a \u0027red action plan\u0027 and would be appropriate for patients with severe or rapidly progressing CKD (stage 4-5), poorly controlled hypertension, significant albuminuria, or acute complications. While this patient has risk factors for progression, her current clinical status does not warrant such intensive monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEvery 3-6 months\u003C/strong\u003E corresponds to an \u0027orange action plan\u0027 in the traffic-light system used for CKD management in primary care. It is appropriate for patients with an eGFR 30-59 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 with microalbuminuria (A2) or an eGFR 30-44 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 with normoalbuminuria (A1).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEvery 2 years\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate for any patient with established CKD, particularly one with comorbidities that increase the risk of progression. This frequency would not allow for timely intervention to slow disease progression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEvery 3 years\u003C/strong\u003E is far too infrequent for monitoring a patient with established CKD. This would pose a significant risk of missing disease progression and complications, especially in a patient with multiple risk factors for CKD progression including hypertension and pre-diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe primary care management of CKD involves regular monitoring of renal function, blood pressure, albuminuria, and management of comorbidities. The frequency of monitoring should be tailored to the individual patient based on disease severity, stability, and risk factors for progression. Guidelines for CKD Management in Primary Care can be used to guide appropriate management and investigations for patients, based on their eGFR and uACR. The patient would need fasting glucose blood tests annually for pre-diabetes as well.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic kidney disease (CKD) management in primary care uses a traffic-light system to determine review frequency based on disease severity and stability.","Patients with stage 3a CKD (eGFR 45-59 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2) with normoalbuminuria require annual review (yellow action plan).","Factors that influence CKD monitoring frequency include eGFR stability, albuminuria, blood pressure control, and presence of comorbidities."],"references":["Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) Management in Primary Care (5th edition). Kidney Health Australia. 2024. Available from: https://assets.kidney.org.au/resources/KHA-CKD-Handbook-5th-Ed-July2024.pdf","Khanam M et al. Chronic kidney disease monitoring in Australian general practice [Internet]. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2019:48 (3). Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/march/chronic-kidney-disease-monitoring-in-australian-ge"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96824"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22283"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96824"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-20T17:05:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-20T17:06:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15248"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114820"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relation